                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1148">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Loomis</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Sherman</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Caracas</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1898-04-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 28, 1898</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 126.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that I have asked the
                    consuls of the United States in Venezuela and at Curaçao to watch in a vigilant
                    manner for the appearance of Spanish men-of-war or privateers and to make a
                    point of asking all ship captains who may come into their ports for information
                    that may be of use to the Government of the United States.</p>
                <p>There are two steam vessels under the American flag still plying between
                    Venezuelan ports and Curaçao. These boats belong to the Red “D” line, of New
                    York.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis D. Loomis.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
